<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1191,1363]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,260,1192,1218]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Remarks</emphasis>
. Specimens of this species were not studied. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Nielson, M. W." box="[902,1073,1191,1218]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 202" refId="ref38859" refString="Nielson, M. W. (2015) A revision of the tribe Coelidiini of the Oriental, Palearctic and Australian biogeographical regions (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Coelidiinae). Insecta Mundi, 0410, 1 - 202." type="book chapter" year="2015">Nielson (2015)</bibRefCitation>
adequately described and illustrated the species based on a male specimen collected from the Hunli area (
<collectingRegion box="[989,1206,1228,1254]" country="India" name="Arunachal Pradesh" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Arunachal Pradesh</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1217,1279,1228,1255]" name="India" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">India</collectingCountry>
). Externally it has similar coloration to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" box="[426,526,1264,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Olidiana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis box="[426,526,1264,1291]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">O. brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but has only a basal yellow band on the forewing. It is also similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Zhang" authorityName="Zhang" authorityYear="1994" box="[1304,1437,1264,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Calodia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lii">
<emphasis box="[1304,1358,1264,1291]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">C. lii</emphasis>
Zhang
</taxonomicName>
but can be differentiated by the pygofer with truncate dorsal half, more sharply tapered caudodorsal margin and by the absence of a caudoventral lobe (
<figureCitation box="[553,658,1336,1363]" captionStart="FIGURES 14" captionStartId="49.[151,264,1761,1786]" captionTargetBox="[255,1330,207,1700]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[233,1354,181,1741]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURES 14 A–N. Species of Calodia, male genitalia. A–D. C. bicompressa Nielson; E–G. C. fusca (Melichar); H–K. C. paraostenta Nielson; L–N. C. propennata Nielson. Modified and reproduced from Nielson 2015 (Figs. A–D), Nielson 1982 (Figs. E–G) and Nielson 1991 (Figs. H–N)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3366572/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 14 L</figureCitation>
) and by the glabrous subgenital plate.
</paragraph>
